We then obtain for free commutation of the dotted arrows, which don't bring any new information to the table.
Therefore, in a $1$-category, the monoids correspond to simplicial objects $M_\bullet$ such that for each $[n]\in\Delta$, the morphisms $e_i:M_n\to M_1$ obtained from the edge maps \[
    [1]\xrightarrow{\set{i,i+1}}[n]
\] identify $M_n$ with $M_1^n$.
This is the so-called \textdef{Segal condition}.

\begin{definition}
    Let\/ $\cC$ an\/ $\infty$-category possessing a terminal object.
    A \textdef{monoid}\footnotemark{} in\/ $\cC$ is a simplicial object\/ $M_\bullet$ of\/ $\cC$ verifying the Segal condition.
    We denote by\/ \[
        \catMon*(\cC) \subseteq \catFun*(\Delta^\op,\cC)
    \] the full subcategory of monoids.
    In the following we will almost always abuse language and write simply\/ $M$ both for the monoid\/ $M_\bullet$ and the underlying object\/ $M_1$.
\end{definition}
\footnotetext{Aka $E_1$-monoid or $E_1$-space.}

In a $1$-category, a group object is usually presented as sporting a new inversion map satisfying a bunch of new relations.
Attempting to generalise this directly would lead us straight to combinatorial hell, so we won't.
Instead, we reformulate "being a group" as a \textit{property} on a monoid $M$.
This is in fact very easy.

\begin{definition}
    A monoid with multiplication\/ $m$ is \textdef{grouplike}, or a \textdef{group}, if the shear map \[
        (\pi_1,m) : \begin{aligned}M^2&\to M^2 \\(x,y)&\mapsto(x,xy)\end{aligned}
    \] is an isomorphism.
    Let\/ $\catGrp*(\cC)$ the full subcategory of\/ $\catMon*(\cC)$ consisting of grouplike monoids.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Relation to the commutative version}

Recall that Paul defined commutative monoids in $\cC$ as the full subcategory $\catCMon(\cC)$ of functors $\catFinSet^\catpart\to\cC$ satisfying the analoguous Segal condition.
In order to define the underlying non-commutative monoid it suffices to find the appropriate inclusion $\Delta^\op\to\catFinSet^\catpart$ along which to restrict.

\medskip
Fix $[n]\in\Delta$.
We send it to $[n-1]\in\catFinSet$, the set with $n$ elements (indexed from $0$ to $n-1$).
Note that the inner face maps act on a monoid by multiplying two adjacent elements in an $(n+1)$-tuple.
We therefore assign to $d^i:[n+1]\to[n]$ (where $0<i<n+1$) the function $[n]\to[n-1]$ defined by \[
    j\mapsto\begin{cases}
    j & \text{if }0\leq j\leq i-1\\
    j-1 &\text{if }i\leq j\leq n-1
    .\end{cases}
\]

On the other hand the outer face maps $d^0,d^n$ acts on a monoid by forgetting the first (resp. last) element of an $n+1$-tuple.
Thus we assign to $d^0$ the partial function sending $0$ nowhere and $1\leq j\leq n$ to $j-1$.
Dually to $d^n$ assign the partial function fixing all $0\leq j\leq n-1$ and sending $n$ nowhere.


Finally, a degeneracy map $s^i:[n]\to[n+1]$ simply inserts the unit at the corresponding index.
We assign to it the function $[n-1]\to[n]$ defined by \[
    j\mapsto\begin{cases}
    j & \text{if }0\leq j\leq i-1\\
    j+1 &\text{if }i\leq j\leq n-1
    .\end{cases}
\]

It may be verified that these assignments verify the simplicial identities and extend to the desired fully faithful functor $\Delta^\op\to\catFinSet^\catpart$.


\section{Looping, delooping}

\subsection{Looping}

In the homotopy I course, we have seen that the loop object $\Loop X$ of a pointed topological space admits a group structure in $\cathTop$.
Recall the definition, \[\begin{tikzcd}
	{\Loop X} & {\Path(X)} \\
	{*} & X
	\arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["\lrcorner"{anchor=center, pos=0.125}, draw=none, from=1-1, to=2-2]
	\arrow[from=1-2, to=2-2]
	\arrow["x"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
.\end{tikzcd}\]
As the map $\Path(X)\to X$ is a fibration, this strict pullback is in fact a homotopy pullback; and as $\Path(X)\simeq*$ it may be better understood as the homotopy pullback $\Loop X=*\times_X*$.

In a general $\infty$-category $\cC$, this is how we define the loop object of a pointed $X$.
We will now endow it with a (natural!) group structure, which in the specific case of $\cC=\catAn$ retrieves the one we know and love upon passing to the homotopy category.
In order to perform this feat, we seek a simplicial object extending $\Loop X\to*$.
There is a natural candidate one, the \v Cech nerve of the map $x:*\to X$!

Recall that this is a simplicial object $\vC(x)_\bullet$ whose $n$-simplices are given by \[
    \vC(x)_n=*\times_X*\times_X\cdots\times_X*=*^{n+1}_X
.\]
Some abstract nonsense (see \cite[lem.~4.1.9]{cnossen:ha} for details) inform us that the edge maps $e_i : \vC(x)_n\to\vC(x)_1=\Loop X$ do indeed identify $\vC(x)_n$ with $\Loop_X^n$.

\begin{remark}\label{rmk:cech-functorial}
    The \v Cech nerve is functorial, and can be written as the composite \[
        \vC_\bullet : \catFun^*([1],\cC)\simeq\catFun*([1]^\op,\cC)\xrightarrow{j_*}\catFun*(\Delta^\op_+,\cC)\xrightarrow{i^*}\catFun*(\Delta^\op,\cC)
    ,\] where $j_*$ is the right Kan extension along the inclusion $j:[1]^\op\to\Delta_+^\op$ sending $0$ to $[-1]$ and $1$ to $[0]$, and $i^*$ is the restriction along the inclusion $i:\Delta^\op\to\Delta^\op_+$.
    See \cite[def.~4.1.6 and disc.~4.1.7]{cnossen:ha} for details.
\end{remark}

Let's check that this is sensible by looking closer at the case of $\catTop$ with the Quillen model structure.
By replacing the maps $*\to X$ with the fibration $\Path(X)\to X$, we can compute explicitly \[
    \vC(x)_n = \Path(X)^{n+1}_X
.\]
I like to view this as the space of $(n+1)$ tendrils extending from $x$ and rejoigning at some other unspecified point.

