On figure \ref{fig:concrete-cech-nerve}, we see that the "abstract" monoid structure on $\vC(x)$ corresponds exactly to the "concrete" monoid structure on $\Loop X$.
This is reassuring.
Now examples are good and all, but we still have to prove something.

\begin{proposition}\label{prop:loop-group}
    Let $x:*\to X$ a pointed object in an $\infty$-category $\cC$ with the appropriate pullbacks.
    Then $\vC(x)$ is a grouplike monoid with underlying object $\Loop X$.
\end{proposition}

We will write equally $\Loop X$ for the object and the group object.
When the two need to be distinguished, the object shall be denoted by $(\Loop X)_1$.

\begin{proof}
    Because we have admitted that $\vC(x)_n\simeq(\Loop X)^n$ through $(e_0,\ldots,e_{n-1})$, it remains only to check that the shear map $(\pi_1,m):\vC(x)_2\to\vC(x)_2$ is an isomorphism.
    Moreover it suffices to check the statement in the case of animae by an application of Yoneda lemma.
    Indeed, for any object $Y$ of $\cC$, \[
        \Map(Y,\Loop X) = \Loop\Map(Y,X)
    \] and the shear map for $X$ is sent to the shear map for $\Map(Y,X)$.
    Furthermore, whether a map is an isomorphism can be tested at the level of homotopy categories.
    But we already know that (the weak homotopy type of) the loop space of a pointed topological space is a group object!
\end{proof}


\subsection{Delooping}

Much like how it is false in general that $\Sigma\Loop X\simeq X$, we cannot always recover $X$ from $\Loop X$.
However, we will see shortly that in the case of animae, we actually remember the whole connected component of the chosen point $x$.
The best approximation of an inverse operation to $\Loop{}$ is the \textdef{classifying space} $\B{}$.

\begin{definition}
    Let $\cC$ an $\infty$-category with the appropriate geometric realizations, and $M_\bullet$ a monoid.
    Its \textdef{classifying space} $\B M$ is the colimit \[
        \B M = |M| = \colim_{\Delta^\op}M_\bullet \in\cC
    .\]
    This object is naturally pointed by the map $*=M_0\to|M|=\B M$, defining a functor \[
        \B:\catMon*(\cC)\to\cC_*
    .\]
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
    By the pointwise formula for Kan extensions, the functor $B$ may be expressed as the composite \[
        \catMon*(\cC)\subseteq\catFun*(\Delta^\op,\cC)\xrightarrow{i_!}\catFun*(\Delta_+^\op,\cC)\xrightarrow{j^*}\catFun*([1]^\op,\cC)
    ,\] where $i_!$ is the left Kan extension along the inclusion $i:\Delta\to\Delta_+$ and $j^*$ the restriction along the same inclusion as in remark \ref{rmk:cech-functorial}.
\end{remark}

\begin{proposition}
    Let $\cC$ an $\infty$-category with finite limits and geometric realizations.
    The loop space and classifying space functors define an adjunction \[
        \B : \catMon*(\cC) \dashv\, \cC_* : \Loop
    .\]
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
    We have a more general adjunction \[\begin{tikzcd}
        {\catFun*(\Delta^\op,\cC)} & {\catFun*(\Delta_+^\op,\cC)} & {\catFun*([1]^\op,\cC)}
        \arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{i_!}", shift left=2, from=1-1, to=1-2]
        \arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{i^*}", shift left=2, from=1-2, to=1-1]
        \arrow[""{name=2, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{j^*}", shift left=2, from=1-2, to=1-3]
        \arrow[""{name=3, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "{j_*}", shift left=2, from=1-3, to=1-2]
        \arrow["\dashv"{anchor=center, rotate=-90}, draw=none, from=0, to=1]
        \arrow["\dashv"{anchor=center, rotate=-90}, draw=none, from=2, to=3]
    \end{tikzcd}\] of which $\B{}$ and $\Loop{}$ are the restriction to full subcategories.
\end{proof}


\begin{remark}
    Remark that over animae (or any $\infty$-topos), $\cat B$ preserves products.
    In particular, it preserves monoid and group objects.
    If we believe in the heuristic that an abelian group is a group object in group objects, this would mean that whenever $A$ is an abelian group object, so is $\B A$.
    I wanted to prove this but there was no time.
\end{remark}


\section{The recognition principle for loop spaces}

What happens to $\Loop\B M$ if $M$ was already a group?
Under which conditions does $X$ equal $\B\Loop X$?
All of those deeply existential questions and more are answered by the following
\begin{theorem}[Recognition principle]\label{thm:recog}
    Let\/ $M$ a monoid in\/ $\catAn$ and let\/ $X$ a pointed anima.
    Then \begin{enumerate}
        \item\label{thm:recog:isom-iff-grp} The unit map\/ $M\to\Loop\B M$ is an isomorphism if and only if\/ $M$ is grouplike.
        \item\label{thm:recog:connected} The pointed anima\/ $\B M$ is always connected, and in fact
        \item\label{thm:recog:counit} The counit\/ $\B\Loop X\to X$ is the inclusion of the connected component of the basepoint.
    \end{enumerate}
    In particular, the adjunction $\B{}\dashv\Loop{}$ restricts to an equivalence $\catGrp*(\catAn)\to\catAn_*^{\geq1}$ between animated groups and pointed connected animae.
\end{theorem}

\framebox{Slogan in \textit{flexeur} language: any grouplike $E_1$-space is equivalent to a loop space.}

\begin{remark}
    The same is true in a presheaf topos because all these constructions are taken pointwise.
    In fact it holds in any $\infty$-topos, because left-exact localisation commutes with both colimits (hence $\B{}$) and finite limits (hence $\Loop{}$).
\end{remark}

\begin{proof}\cite[p.~131]{cnossen:ha}
    We first prove claim \ref{thm:recog:connected}.
    The $\pi_0:\catAn\to\catSet$ is left adjoint to inclusion of sets as discrete spaces, so commutes with colimits.
    Hence \[
        \pi_0(\B M) = \colim_{\Delta^\op}\pi_0(M_\bullet) = \colim_{[n]\in\Delta^\op} \left[
            \begin{tikzcd}[row sep=tiny,column sep=small]
                \cdots & {\pi_0M^2} & \pi_0M & {*}
                \arrow[dotted, from=1-1, to=1-2]
                \arrow[from=1-2, to=1-3]
                \arrow[shift left=2, from=1-2, to=1-3]
                \arrow[shift right=2, from=1-2, to=1-3]
                \arrow[shift left, from=1-3, to=1-2]
                \arrow[shift right, from=1-3, to=1-2]
                \arrow[shift left, from=1-3, to=1-4]
                \arrow[shift right, from=1-3, to=1-4]
                \arrow[from=1-4, to=1-3]
            \end{tikzcd}
        \right] = *
    \] so that $\B M$ is connected.

    Assume \ref{thm:recog:isom-iff-grp} for now and prove \ref{thm:recog:counit}.
    As $\B\Loop X$ is connected, the counit lands in the connected component $X^\circ$, and we have to show $\B\Loop X\to X^\circ$ is an isomorphism.
    Because both sides are connected and homotopy groups form a conservative family of functors, it suffices to check that \[
        \Loop X\simeq\Loop\B\Loop X\to\Loop X^\circ
    \] is an isomorphism.
    This is by definition of $\Loop{}$.

    It remains to show the most interesting claim \ref{thm:recog:isom-iff-grp}.
    The forward direction follows from proposition \ref{prop:loop-group}.
    For the converse direction, it suffices to prove that $M_1\to(\Loop\B M)_1$ is an isomorphism as it will then induce an isomorphism at all levels.
    This map comes from the commutative square \[\begin{tikzcd}
        M_1\ar[d,"d_1"]\ar[r,"d_0"] & M_0\ar[d]\simeq* \\
        M_0\simeq*\ar[r] & \B M
    ,\end{tikzcd}\] that we must check is cartesian.

    \medskip
    For this, we shall use the following \vskip-8pt
    \begin{theorem}[Universality of colimits {\cite[6.1.3.9]{HTT}}]
        Let\/ $I$ a small\/ $\infty$-categories,\/ $\bar F,\bar G:I^\triangleright\to\catAn$ cocones over functors\/ $F,G$, and $\bar\alpha:\bar F\to\bar G$ a natural transformation.
        Assume that the restriction\/ $\alpha:F\to G$ is cartesian, in the sense that for every\/ $i\to j$ in\/ $I$ the square \[\begin{tikzcd}
            F(i)\ar[d,"\alpha_i"]\ar[r] & F(j)\ar[d,"\alpha_j"] \\
            G(i)\ar[r] & G(j)
        \end{tikzcd}\] is cartesian.
        Assume further\/ $\bar G$ to be a colimit.
        Then\/ $\bar F$ is a colimit if and only if\/ $\bar\alpha$ is cartesian, which is to say all the squares \[\begin{tikzcd}
            F(i)\ar[d,"\alpha_i"]\ar[r] & \bar F(\infty)\ar[d,"\bar\alpha_\infty"] \\
            G(i)\ar[r] & \bar G(\infty)
        \end{tikzcd}\] are cartesian also.
    \end{theorem}
    We admit this and carry on with the proof of the recognition principle.

    Let $I=\Delta^\op$ so that $I^\triangleright=\Delta_+^\op$, as well as $G=M$ and $\bar G(\infty)=\B M$.
    Set $\bar F[n]=\bar G[n+1]$, obtained from $\bar G$ by discarding the purple arrows below:
    % https://q.uiver.app/#
    \[\begin{tikzcd}[row sep=tiny]
        & {\bar F[1]} & {\bar F[0]} & {\bar F[-1]} \\
        \cdots & {M^2} & M & {*} & {\B M} \\
        & \textcolor{rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}{{\bar G[2]}} & \textcolor{rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}{{\bar G[1]}} & \textcolor{rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}{{\bar G[0]}} & \textcolor{rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}{{\bar G[-1]}}
        \arrow[shift left=3, from=2-1, to=2-2]
        \arrow[shift right=3, color={rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}, from=2-1, to=2-2]
        \arrow[shift left, from=2-1, to=2-2]
        \arrow[shift right, from=2-1, to=2-2]
        \arrow[from=2-2, to=2-1]
        \arrow[shift left=2, color={rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}, from=2-2, to=2-1]
        \arrow[shift right=2, from=2-2, to=2-1]
        \arrow[from=2-2, to=2-3]
        \arrow["{d^0}", shift left=2, from=2-2, to=2-3]
        \arrow["{d^2}"', shift right=2, color={rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}, from=2-2, to=2-3]
        \arrow[shift left, color={rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}, from=2-3, to=2-2]
        \arrow[shift right, from=2-3, to=2-2]
        \arrow["{d^0}", shift left, from=2-3, to=2-4]
        \arrow["{d^1}"', shift right, color={rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}, from=2-3, to=2-4]
        \arrow[color={rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}, from=2-4, to=2-3]
        \arrow[color={rgb,255:red,92;green,92;blue,214}, from=2-4, to=2-5]
    \end{tikzcd}\]
    Define also $\bar\alpha_n=d_{n+1}$.
    If we knew that $\alpha$ was cartesian and $\bar F$ a colimit, then universality would give us exactly the required cartesian square for $i=0$.
    That $\bar F$ is a colimit follows from another very general lemma, whose statement and proof we defer until later.
    Now for cartesianity of $\alpha$, we prove this by cases.

    \begin{enumerate}[C{a}se 1 --]
        \item\label{thm:recog:step:shear} The map $d^1:[1]\to[0]$.
        In this case, the square reduces to \[\begin{tikzcd}
            M^2 \ar[d,"\pi_0"']\ar[r,"m"] & M \ar[d] \\
            M \ar[r] & *
        \end{tikzcd}\] which is a pullback precisely because $M$ is grouplike.

        \item The map $d^0:[n+1]\to[n]$.
        The square reduces to \[\begin{tikzcd}[column sep=22ex]
            M^{n+2} \ar[d,"(m_0\ldots m_{n+1})\mapsto(m_0\ldots m_n)"']\ar[r,"(m_0\ldots m_{n+1})\mapsto(m_1\ldots m_{n+1})"] & M^{n+1} \ar[d,"(m_0\ldots m_n)\mapsto(m_0\ldots m_{n-1})"]\\
