        \end{tikzcd}\] which is always a pullback.

        \item The map $d^i:[n+1]\to[n]$ for $0<i<n+1$.
        The square reduces to \[\begin{tikzcd}[column sep=31ex]
            M^{n+2} \ar[d,"(m_0\ldots m_{n+1})\mapsto(m_0\ldots m_n)"']\ar[r,"(m_0\ldots m_{n+1})\mapsto(m_0\ldots{,}m_{i-1}m_i{,}\ldots m_{n+1})"] & M^{n+1} \ar[d,"(m_0\ldots m_n)\mapsto(m_0\ldots m_{n-1})"]\\
            M^{n+1} \ar[r,"(m_0\ldots m_n)\mapsto (m_0\ldots{,}m_{i-1}m_i{,}\ldots m_n)"'] & M^n
        \end{tikzcd}\] which is also always a pullback.

        \item The map $d^{n+1}:[n+1]\to[n]$.
        The square reduces to \[\begin{tikzcd}[column sep=24ex]
            M^{n+2} \ar[d,"(m_0\ldots m_{n+1})\mapsto(m_0\ldots m_n)"']\ar[r,"(m_0\ldots m_{n+1})\mapsto(m_0\ldots m_nm_{n+1})"] & M^{n+1} \ar[d,"(m_0\ldots m_n)\mapsto(m_0\ldots m_{n-1})"]\\
            M^{n+1} \ar[r,"(m_0\ldots m_n)\mapsto (m_0\ldots m_{n-1})"'] & M^n
        \end{tikzcd}\] which is the square of \ref{thm:recog:step:shear} multiplied by $M^n$, hence a pullback.

        \item The map $s^i:[n]\to[n+1]$.
        As $s^i$ is a section of $d^i$, by the pasting law and the previous steps, the required square is a pullback.

        \item A general map in $\Delta_+^\op$.
        It factors as a product of faces and degeneracies.
        By the pasting law, the required square is a pullback.
    \end{enumerate}
    This finishes the proof.
\end{proof}

As promised, here is the lemma for checking that $\bar F$ is a colimit.
Introduce first the category of extra degeneracies, $\Delta_+^\catdeg$, as the wide subcategory of $\Delta$ whose morphisms are the maps $\varphi: [n]\to[m]$ satisfying $\varphi(n)=m$.
This includes all the codegeneracies, and all the coface maps save for $d_{n+1}:[n]\to[n+1]$.
As a result, a functor out of $(\Delta_+^\catdeg)^\op$ looks like a diagram
% https://q.uiver.app/#
\[\begin{tikzcd}[row sep=tiny]
	\cdots & {X_{1+1}} & {X_{0+1}} & {X_{-1+1}}
	\arrow[shift left=3, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[from=1-2, to=1-1]
	\arrow[shift left=2, color={rgb,255:red,214;green,92;blue,92}, from=1-2, to=1-1]
	\arrow[shift right=2, from=1-2, to=1-1]
	\arrow[from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left=2, from=1-2, to=1-3]
	\arrow[shift left, color={rgb,255:red,214;green,92;blue,92}, from=1-3, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift right, from=1-3, to=1-2]
	\arrow[shift left, from=1-3, to=1-4]
	\arrow[color={rgb,255:red,214;green,92;blue,92}, from=1-4, to=1-3]
\end{tikzcd}\] in which we understand the red arrows as "extra degeneracies".
The index notation was not chosen randomly; there is a faithful functor $(+1):\Delta_+\to\Delta_+^\catdeg$ sending $[n]$ to $[n+1]$.

\begin{lemma}[Extra degeneracies argument]
    Let $\cC$ and $\infty$-category and $\bar X:\Delta_+^\op\to\cC$ an augmented simplicial object.
    Suppose that $\bar X$ has extra degeneracies, in the sense that $\bar X=\bar Y|_{\Delta_+}$ for some $\bar Y:(\Delta_+^\catdeg)^\op\to\cC$.
    Then $\bar X$ is a colimit cocone.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
    The composite inclusion $\Delta\subseteq\Delta_+\hookrightarrow\Delta_+^\catdeg$ is left adjoint to the inclusion $\Delta_+^\catdeg\subseteq\Delta$.
    Indeed for any natural numbers $n$, $m$ any ordered map $\varphi:[n]\to[m]$ extends uniquely to $[n+1]\to[m]$ if we impose the condition that $\varphi(n+1)=m$.
    By \cite[cor.~19.5.6]{cnossen:ha}, this implies that $(+1)|_\Delta$ is initial, and hence that \[
        (+1)^\op:\Delta^\op\to(\Delta_+^\catdeg)^\op
    \] is final.
    In other words \[
        \colim_{\Delta^\op} X_\bullet = \colim_{\Delta^\op} Y_{\bullet+1} = \colim_{(\Delta_+^\catdeg)^\op} Y_\bullet = Y_0 = X_{-1}
    \] because $[0]$ is terminal in $(\Delta_+^\catdeg)^\op$.
\end{proof}


